# Web User Interface 

The ADS Go Fast User Interface \(UI\) allows users to configure pipelines in a metadata drive approach\. The User Interface performs CRUD operations to the __ADS\_Config__ database, which is referenced by various systems such as Azure Data Factory when executing pipelines\. The sections below discuss features of the ADS Go Fast Web UI, definitions for configurable fields, and instructions on how to change configurations\. 

## Login 

### Authentication 

By default, authentication to the Web UI uses Azure AD Authentication to authenticate users belonging to the Azure AD Groups “__DevGroup__” for non\-production and “__ProdGroup__” for production\. If you wish to make changes to the allowed AD Groups in Azure, please refer to the As Built Guide as we this guide is focused on configuring properties within the User Interface\. 

To login to the app, refer to steps below: 

1. Access the web URL in your browser
2. Provide your email address and password to sign\-in 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Approve the sign\-in request with your secondary device \(multi\-factor authentication\)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Logical model

__Definitions__

- __System__: a system corresponds to a collection of datasets\. For example, a source system database or a collection of files\. 
- __System Property__: a system property is properties that are associated with a system\. These provide additional system configuration\. 
- __Task: __a task corresponds to a dataset\. For example, a database table or a file\. A task can also correspond to executing a transformation script\. 
- __Task Property: __a task property is properties that are associated with a task\. These provide additional task configuration\. 
- __Source Connection: __the source connection is the connection string used to connect to the source system\. 
- __Target Connection:__ the target connection is the connection string used to connect to the target store e\.g\. SQL DB or Data Lake\. 
- __Schedule:__ a task schedule corresponds to the schedule in which the task runs e\.g\. every 15 mins or once a day\. 
- __Task Instance:__ a task instance is a single run of the task\. For example, if a Task was scheduled to run once a day, then a task instance would be created when the schedule is run\. 
- __Data Factory Log: __the data factory log is a table containing detailed log information of system and task runs\. 

To configure ADS Go Fast, please read through the steps below in order\. We recommend configuring Maintenance Data first as the latter steps have dependencies on the Maintenance Data\.

## Users

Users who are added into the __Data Platform \- Configuration Portal __Azure AD group will be granted access to the application without any access to the content within it\. 

The user’s record will be created upon the first time the user signs\-in to the application\. 

The ADS Go Fast UI admins can then perform one of the following to the user’s record: 

- Grant user admin privileges 
- Grant user access to view and edit specified Systems 

__User Index Page__: 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

__User Permissions Page__: 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

To grant users access to specific systems \(1\): 

1. From the User Index page, select “Edit” for a specific user 
2. Tick the selected Systems you wish to grant the user View/Edit access to\. 
3. Click Save

To grant users admin privileges \(2\): 

1. From the User Index page, select “Edit” for a specific user 
2. Tick Access Type: “Admin” – the user will have access to all Systems and ability to change configurations in the “Maintenance Data” pages 
3. Click Save 

## Settings

To change general settings in the ADS Go Fast __ADS\_Config__ database, refer to the steps below: 

1. Select __Maintenance Data__ 
2. Select __Settings__
3. Change settings as required\. 
4. Select __Save__

## Schedules

Schedules are used to specify the time interval for task loads\. Created tasks will run against a specified schedule\. 

__Schedule example__:  
RACWA has 100 tasks to run daily, and 50 tasks to run every hour\. The ADS Go Fast User creates 100 tasks and specifies the schedule to “Once a day”, and then creates 50 tasks and specifies the schedule to “Once every hour”\. 

### Index

The index for the schedule page appears as so: 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

### Create new 

To create a new schedule, refer to the steps below: 

Select __Create new__ 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Change the fields as required 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Select __Create__ 

- The preceding steps have successfully created the schedule in the Web UI\. This Web UI schedule will be used to determine systems that need to be executed\.
- The following steps will now create the schedule in ADF\. This schedule will be used to run the ADF pipelines\. Only Web UI schedules that have not run yet, will be picked up and executed\. 

1. Go to the Azure Data Factory Resource
2. Select __Triggers__
3. Select __New__ > Create a schedule that has the __*same name*__ and information as the Web UI schedule > Set Activated to “Yes”\. The ADF schedule must have the same name as the Web UI schedule\.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Select __OK__
2. Go to “Pipe\_Master\_Generic\_Schedule\_Load”
3. Select __Add Trigger__ > __New Edit__ > Select the Trigger Name you have just created
4. Leave the Parameter “Schedule” as blank

![](data:image/png;base64,)

1. Select __Save__
2. You have successfully set up schedules\. ADF will now automatically trigger runs based on the schedule and run any systems that are tagged to the Web UI schedule\. 

### Edit

To edit a schedule, refer to the steps below: 

Select __Edit__ 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Change the fields as required 

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Select __Save__

### Delete 

To delete a schedule, refer to the steps below: 

Select __Delete__ for a schedule you wish to delete

## Task Instances

Tasks Instances are all the individual runs for a task\. A new task instance is created for each scheduled window a task is required to run\. For example, a schedule window exists for TaskX for Once a Day\. At the set time each day, a new task instance is created with a status of “Untried”\. 

A task instance can contain multiple runs\. For example, a task instance could contain a single run which failed, and the same task instance could contain a single run which was successful\. Both runs belong to the same task instance\. After the run is complete, the task instance’s status will update to “Success” or “Failure – Retry” depending on success or failure\.
